Newspaper Guild of New York Records

Contents

Series I: Early Records: General Files, 1935-1950

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content Note

Series I: Early Records: General Files, 1935-1950, documents the activities and operations of the NGNY and the ANG in their early years. The series includes correspondence, committee files, officers' files, election files, convention records, publications, and subject files.

Series II: Early Records: Shop Files, 1935-1950

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content Note

Series II: Early Records: Shop Files, 1935-1950, documents shops organized in the early years of the NGNY, including those at the Brooklyn Eagle, Daily News, Herald Tribune, Journal American, Mirror, New York Post, New York Times, Newsweek, Time, and World Telegram.

Scope and Content Note

Series IV: Minutes, 1951-1991

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content Note

Series IV: Minutes, 1951-1991, contains the post-1950 minutes of American Newspaper Guild Executive Board, NGNY Executive Board and NGNY Executive Committee meetings, as well as minutes of NGNY general membership meetings, representative assembly, committees and other local and regional entities.

Scope and Content Note

The Newspaper Guild of New York, launched in 1934, is an labor union for people in the news and media business, including print, photo, video, and digital journalists, as well as employees in advertising, circulation and other related areas. They represent about 3,000 employees at New York area-based media organizations and their respective bureaus around the nation. The website contains information on current bureaus represented by the union and news listings.

Physical Characteristics and Technical Requirements

Due to technical or privacy issues, archived websites may not be exact copies of the original website at the time of the web crawl. Certain file types will not be captured dependent on how they are embedded in the site. Other parts of websites that the crawler has difficulty capturing includes Javascript, streaming content, database-driven content, and highly interactive content. Full-Text searches of archived websites are available at https://archive-it.org/organizations/567.
